  "text": "Firefox crashes when processing CSS calc() with extreme values due to numeric overflow issues in the calc() expression evaluation pipeline.\n\n**Key Components:**\n\n1. **Parsing Layer (servo/components/style/values/specified/calc.rs)**: Parses CSS calc() expressions from user stylesheets into a CalcNode AST structure. The parser handles mathematical functions like calc(), min(), max(), clamp(), round(), mod(), rem(), hypot(), and trigonometric functions.\n\n2. **Generic Calc Node Implementation (servo/components/style/values/generics/calc.rs)**: Contains the core CalcNode<L> enum and the critical resolve_internal() method (lines 928-1184) that evaluates calc() expressions. The overflow vulnerability likely exists in:\n   - Line 1105-1107: round() function operations where `value / step` and arithmetic with large values can overflow\n   - Line 1153: Hypot calculation with `v.powi(2)` squaring potentially extreme values\n   - Line 1165: Hypot accumulation with `v + child_value.powi(2)` where large squared values overflow\n   - Line 941: Invert operation with `1.0 / v` can produce infinity/NaN\n\n3. **Computed Value Layer (servo/components/style/values/computed/length_percentage.rs)**: The CalcLengthPercentage struct (line 927) contains the resolve() method (lines 991-1008) that converts percentages to lengths and applies clamping through AllowedNumericType::clamp().\n\n4. **FFI Bridge (servo/ports/geckolib/glue.rs)**: The Servo_ResolveCalcLengthPercentage() function (lines 9208-9213) is the C++ entry point that calls calc.resolve(computed::Length::new(basis)).px() to get the final pixel value.\n\n5. **C++ Integration (layout/style/ServoStyleConstsInlines.h)**: The StyleCalcLengthPercentage::ResolveToCSSPixels() method (lines 726-728) bridges C++ code to the Rust FFI, then uses the result which can have unclamped extreme values.\n\n**Root Cause**: The resolve_internal() method performs unchecked floating-point arithmetic on potentially extreme values. Operations like squaring (powi(2)) with values near f32::MAX (3.4e38) or operations with infinity/NaN during hypot() calculation can cause undefined behavior or overflow that crashes the renderer. The clamping that occurs later in the resolve() method of CalcLengthPercentage only clamps after the potentially overflowing calculations are complete, allowing overflow crashes to occur before clamping can take effect."
}

